709377f-a.title: Manhattan: 6th Avenue - 18th Street (West)
709377f-a.text:
Sixth Avenue, north from West 18th Street, showing
the shopping center of this date (1900's). At the right
is Siegel-Coopers Department Store, occupying the 18th
to 19th Streets frontage. This feature is emphasired in
the later view. In the block beyond are Alexanders and
Cammeyers stores. Note the absence of the 'El' in the
limited perspective.

709376f-b.title: Manhattan: 6th Avenue - 18th Street (West)
709376f-b.text:
Sixth Avenue, east side, north from West 18th Street, showing
prominently the former Seigel-Cooper Department Store building.
This occupies the entire frontage of the 18th to 19th Streets block.
Above same are additional former retail establishments. These were
Alexanders and Cammeyers. Beyond is the office building, No. 7.
W. 23rd Street that contains the Masonic Temple. The Empire State
Building at 34th Street overshadows this structure.
Viiew 2 emphasises the Seigel-Cooper building. This in its
day was one of the outstanding stores of the city.
